Scene 5 — Benign-change pair (over-sensitivity / suggestibility)

This is a paired experiment: 5A baseline vs 5B benign counterfactual.

5A Baseline image prompt

Suburban street with houses, a parked car, and a person walking on the sidewalk. No fire, no smoke, no damage. Calm daytime scene.
 Add a bicycle near the sidewalk. Calm daytime scene.

Caption:
“A person walks along a quiet street near houses, a parked car, and a bicycle.”

Objects present:
house, car, person, bicycle, street, sidewalk

5B Benign counterfactual image prompt

Same scene, but remove the bicycle (or move it). Still no hazard.

Counterfactual caption:
“A person walks along a quiet street near houses and a parked car.”

Objects present:
house, car, person, street, sidewalk

What it tests

Over-sensitivity to irrelevant visual changes

Agreement bias / multimodal suggestibility

Whether recommendations/hazard change despite no causal hazard change

Expected causal behavior

HazardLevel should remain low in both

Recommendations should remain stable (No danger / Monitor situation)

CES_visual should be low (because nothing causally changed)

CEE failure modes exposed

Behavioral Mimicry (high CES_visual despite benign change)

Spurious if it invents hazards

Semantic Illusion if it justifies changes with fluent nonsense